Ford Gobike¶

by Reem Osama El-Telbani¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this project we'll be analyzing data associated with information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

the dataset includes:

183412 rows , and 16 variables

Variables meaning:

1 - Trip Duration (seconds)

2 - Start Time and Date Identification of each appointment.

3 - End Time and Date Male or Female.

4 - Start Station ID: The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.

5 - Start Station Name The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment.

6 - Start Station Latitude How old is the patient.

7 - Start Station Longitude Where the appointment takes place.

8 - End Station ID True of False . (scholarship for poor people in Brazil).

9 - End Station Name True or False.

10 - End Station Latitude True or False.

11 - End Station Longitude True or False.

12 - Bike ID True or False.

13 - User Type (Subscriber or Customer Subscriber = Member or Customer = Casual): 14 - Member Birth Year True or False.

15 - Member Gender Female, Male, or Other.

16 - Bike Sahre For all Trip No or Yes.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 rides in the dataset with 16 features(duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip). there are 11 numeric features , and 5 categorical features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

there are interesting features like the trip duration in seconds i think there would be useful insights came from it if we see the relation between it and other features.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

i think taht user type, age and gender are the most feature will support my investigation , in which user type do more rides than the other , and which of them spend more duration.

Before we do Exploration we are going to make some cleansing in our data¶

-Dropping the un needed columns

-Dropping rows contains null values

-Dropping the duplicated rows if found after dropping nulls

-Adding a new column have the age of each user

-Change start time and end time data types

-Change member_birth_year data type to int64

In [61]:
def calculate_age (born_year):
    today = date.today()
    return today.year - born_year
In [62]:

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

-yes there was

-the duration is very skewed to the right and that is logic that not all people can take the rides for a long durations, so most of them are accumlating under 10000 seconds, after removing outlaiers the duration in secound values are skewed to the right but not like what it was.

-a new column was added named age , calculated from the birth year of the users.

-the age is right skewed, the people who are younger tends to do rides more that the older people, but there is ages above 100 which are outlaiers in our case. after removing outlaiers the ages values are normaly destributed .

-the dataset is not balanced with respect to the gender and user types, and those iam going to look deeper if these un balanced categories have a relation between them, later..
